# FACTORY.md

Configuration for [gh-dev-factory](https://clawhub.com/skills/gh-dev-factory).

The factory reads this file at the start of every cycle.

## Workflow

- Branch naming: factory/<issue>-<slug>
- Merge strategy: squash
- Test command: npm test
- Labels: planned (has implementation plan), blocked (skip during scan)

## Boundaries

Files and directories the factory must never modify:

- .github/
- LICENSE

## Human Checkpoints

- Factory may mark PRs ready for review: yes
- Factory may auto-merge approved PRs: no
- Factory may create labels if missing: yes

## Budget

- Billing: api
- Max cycles per day: 10
- Max open PRs: 2
- Scan model: sonnet
- Act model: opus

<!--
Billing options:

api — pay-per-token. Factory tracks estimated cost per cycle.

subscription — Claude Pro/Max via setup-token. Factory paces to avoid
exhausting your 5-hour rolling window and weekly caps.

Model routing:
The scan model handles heartbeat/cron scans, label checks, and queue reads.
The act model handles planning, implementation, code review, and PR work.
Using Sonnet for scans costs ~60x less than Opus per run.
On subscription billing, Sonnet scans barely dent your rate limit window.

Subscription defaults (if billing: subscription):
Interval extends to 4h. Scan + plan use Sonnet. Only implementation uses Opus.
If rate-limited, factory backs off and doubles interval for the rest of the day.
-->

## Previews

- Enabled: yes
- Platform: vercel
- Comment URL on PR: yes
- Teardown on merge: automatic

## Releases

- Versioning: semver
- Tag format: v{major}.{minor}.{patch}
- Changelog source: merged PRs since last tag
- Changelog categories:
  - Features: enhancement label
  - Fixes: bug label
  - Breaking: breaking label or ! in PR title
  - Docs: documentation label

## Production

- Deploy command: vercel --prod
- Health check: https://myapp.com/api/health
- Rollback: vercel rollback
- Auto-deploy on release: no
- Pre-flight:
  - CI must be green on main
  - No open issues labeled blocker

## Rules

<!--
Add one line here whenever the factory gets something wrong.
Each line prevents a future mistake. Examples:

- Always run npm run lint before marking a PR ready
- Never add dependencies without noting why in the PR description
- Integration tests go in tests/integration/, unit tests in tests/unit/
- Don't refactor unrelated code in the same PR
-->
